  "frictions": [
    {
      "agent": "agent-a",
      "id": "f1",
      "refs": [
        "n007"
      ],
      "text": "n007 (guidelines dropped the cholesterol cap) is offered as a Ground for 'eggs are ~neutral', but it is an APPEAL TO AUTHORITY / consensus signal, not direct biological or epidemiological evidence. The grammar has no way to mark that this support is evidential-weak / rhetorical rather than a first-order reason. FLF explicitly wants rhetorical-vs-evidential moves surfaced; a plain Ground edge hides the distinction.",
      "ts": "2026-07-02T15:25:31.082353+00:00"
    },
    {
      "agent": "agent-a",
      "id": "f2",
      "refs": [
        "n004",
        "n013"
      ],
      "text": "A SINGLE source (eggs-001, Hu 1999) yields TWO findings that support DIFFERENT positions: no CVD link in non-diabetics (grounds N1) and higher risk in diabetics (grounds N3). I had to split it into two external_anchor nodes both citing eggs-001. Nothing records that these are the same study, so a reader can't see that one dataset cuts both ways, and double-counting its evidential weight is invisible.",
      "ts": "2026-07-02T15:25:31.149767+00:00"
    },
    {
      "agent": "agent-a",
      "id": "f3",
      "refs": [
        "n008"
      ],
      "text": "n008 (yolks ~185mg cholesterol) is a hard empirical fact that should exit the graph to a food-composition database, but the source pack has no such reference, so I left it as a bare internal claim. The grammar's 'external_anchor must cite a pack ref' rule and the pack's coverage are out of sync; the graph looks internally-grounded where it should touch reality.",
      "ts": "2026-07-02T15:25:31.201095+00:00"
    },
    {
      "agent": "agent-b",
      "id": "f4",
      "refs": [
        "n005",
        "n009"
      ],
      "text": "I placed n005 (diet cholesterol weak effect for most) and n009 (raises LDL, esp. hyper-responders) in one antithesis set as 'in tension', but they are NOT mutually exclusive — both can be true at once (weak on average, strong in a subgroup). Antithesis membership renders them as rivals of equal kind to the N1/N2/N3 answers, overstating the opposition. Need graded / partial tension, not binary set membership.",
      "ts": "2026-07-02T15:25:31.258372+00:00"
    },
    {
      "agent": "agent-c",
      "id": "f5",
      "refs": [
        "n017",
        "n016",
        "n013"
      ],
      "text": "n017 (confounding) does not deny n013 (the diabetic association is real); it attacks the INFERENCE from n013 to a causal reading. Support-only has no undercut edge, so I was forced to invent a positive 'it's causal' node (n016) purely to have something for the confounding claim to be antithesis to. This distorts an argument about inference-strength into a rival factual claim. This is the core relational-sufficiency finding: undercutting defeaters do not fit cleanly.",
      "ts": "2026-07-02T15:25:31.309875+00:00"
    },
    {
      "agent": "agent-a",
      "id": "f6",
      "refs": [
        "n010"
      ],
      "text": "n010 ('elevated LDL causally raises CVD') is a huge separately-contested question (the diet-heart hypothesis) that the egg argument LEANS ON but truncates at a single external anchor (n011). The boundary where we stop decomposing is doing load-bearing work and is semi-arbitrary — the relevance-horizon problem. A reader can't tell whether we endorse n010 or merely need it.",
      "ts": "2026-07-02T15:25:31.374940+00:00"
    },
    {
      "agent": "agent-c",
      "id": "f7",
      "refs": [
        "n015",
        "n003"
      ],
      "text": "n015 ('high-risk people SHOULD limit eggs') is normative but is grounded by purely empirical claims (n003/n013). The grammar marks no is->ought transition, so a value-laden conclusion and a factual ground look identical as nodes and the Ground edge silently crosses the is/ought gap.",
      "ts": "2026-07-02T15:25:31.429931+00:00"
    }
  ],
